e character Charlie Chan, then shows that Asian American writers subject both literary Orientalism and racial stereotyping to double ventriloquism and countermockery. Going on to offer a provocative critique of some textually and culturally homogenizing tendencies exemplified in Maxine Hong Kingston's work and its reception, Huang ends with a study of American translations of contemporary Chinese poetry, which he views as new ethnographies that maintain linguistic and cultural boundaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAmerican literaturexChinese American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexChinese influences. 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aChinese Americans in literature. 0aChinese Americans in mass media. 0aChinese AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aChinese literaturexAppreciationzUnited States. 0aEthnology in literature. 0aImmigrants in literature. 0aIntertextuality. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh  aamy lowell.  aappropriation.  aasia.  achinese poetry.  acritique.  acultural history.  acultural studies.  adisappropriation.  adisplacement.  aethnographer.  aethnographic.  aethnography.  aezra pound.  aimagism.  aimagist poets.  alinguistic ethnography.  alinguistic theory.  alinguistics.  arace issues.  arace.  aracial stereotypes.  aracism.  asocial history.  asocial studies.  astereotypes.  atranspacific.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022886340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092814540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520928145423Coveruhttps://www.degr